<h1>Poker Hand Rankings</h1>

<p class="lead">Understanding poker hand rankings is essential for playing most poker variants. Below are the standard rankings for both 5-card and 3-card hands.</p>

<div class="row mt-4">
  <div class="col-md-6">
    <h2>5-Card Hand Rankings</h2>
    <p>Ranked from highest to lowest:</p>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">1. Royal Flush</h5>
        <p class="card-text">A, K, Q, J, 10, all of the same suit.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: A♠ K♠ Q♠ J♠ 10♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">2. Straight Flush</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Five cards in sequence, all of the same suit.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 9♥ 8♥ 7♥ 6♥ 5♥</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">3. Four of a Kind</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Four cards of the same rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 7♠ 7♥ 7♦ 7♣ K♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">4. Full House</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three of a kind with a pair.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 10♠ 10♥ 10♦ 4♣ 4♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">5. Flush</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Any five cards of the same suit, not in sequence.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: K♦ J♦ 8♦ 6♦ 3♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">6. Straight</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Five cards in sequence, not all of the same suit.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 8♠ 7♥ 6♦ 5♣ 4♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">7. Three of a Kind</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three cards of the same rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: Q♠ Q♥ Q♦ 9♣ 5♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">8. Two Pair</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Two cards of one rank and two cards of another rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: J♠ J♥ 6♦ 6♣ A♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">9. One Pair</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Two cards of the same rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 9♠ 9♥ A♦ K♣ 7♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">10. High Card</h5>
        <p class="card-text">When you haven't made any of the hands above, the highest card plays.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: A♠ K♥ 10♦ 7♣ 4♠</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="col-md-6">
    <h2>3-Card Hand Rankings</h2>
    <p>Used in games like Three Card Poker. Ranked from highest to lowest:</p>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">1. Straight Flush</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three cards in sequence, all of the same suit.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 7♥ 6♥ 5♥</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">2. Three of a Kind</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three cards of the same rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: Q♠ Q♥ Q♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">3. Straight</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three cards in sequence, not all of the same suit.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 9♠ 8♥ 7♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">4. Flush</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Three cards of the same suit, not in sequence.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: K♦ 9♦ 4♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">5. Pair</h5>
        <p class="card-text">Two cards of the same rank.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: 8♠ 8♥ A♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card mb-3">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">6. High Card</h5>
        <p class="card-text">When you haven't made any of the hands above, the highest card plays.</p>
        <p class="text-muted">Example: A♠ K♥ 9♦</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
      <h5>Note on 3-Card Rankings</h5>
      <p>In 3-card poker, a straight is harder to make than a flush, so straights rank higher than flushes (opposite of 5-card poker). Also, there is no two pair since you only have three cards.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row mt-5">
  <div class="col-12">
    <h2>Playing with Wild Cards</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h5 class="card-title">Wild Card Rules</h5>
        <p>When playing with wild cards (such as deuces wild, or games where certain cards are declared wild), the following additional hands become possible:</p>

        <div class="mt-3">
          <h6>Five of a Kind</h6>
          <p>Four cards of the same rank plus a wild card. This is the highest possible hand when playing with wilds, ranking above a royal flush.</p>
          <p class="text-muted">Example: 10♠ 10♥ 10♦ 10♣ 2♠ (where 2s are wild)</p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-3">
          <h6>Wild Card Considerations</h6>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Best Use:</strong> A wild card should be used to make the highest possible hand</li>
            <li><strong>Ties:</strong> When comparing hands, a "natural" hand (without wilds) typically beats an identical hand made with wilds (house rules vary)</li>
            <li><strong>Straight/Flush:</strong> Wild cards can complete straights and flushes</li>
            <li><strong>Duplicate Cards:</strong> In most games, you cannot use a wild card to create an impossible hand (like having five aces when only four exist)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
          <strong>Important:</strong> Wild card rules can vary by game and house rules. Always clarify wild card rules before playing, especially regarding:
          <ul class="mb-0">
            <li>Which cards are wild</li>
            <li>Whether five of a kind is allowed</li>
            <li>How ties are resolved (natural vs. wild)</li>
            <li>Whether wild cards can be used in both high and low hands</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row mt-4">
  <div class="col-12">
    <h2>Additional Notes</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h6>Comparing Hands of the Same Type</h6>
        <p>When two players have the same type of hand, the winner is determined by the rank of the cards:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>High Card:</strong> Compare the highest cards; if tied, compare the next highest, etc.</li>
          <li><strong>Pair/Two Pair/Three of a Kind/Four of a Kind:</strong> Compare the rank of the matching cards first, then kickers</li>
          <li><strong>Straight/Straight Flush:</strong> Compare the highest card in the sequence (ace can be high or low)</li>
          <li><strong>Flush:</strong> Compare cards from highest to lowest</li>
          <li><strong>Full House:</strong> Compare the three of a kind first, then the pair</li>
        </ul>

        <h6 class="mt-3">Suit Rankings</h6>
        <p>In standard poker, suits are equal. No suit is higher than another. However, some games may use suit rankings to break ties or determine bring-in bets (typically: Spades > Hearts > Diamonds > Clubs).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
